<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1436,794,1143]" pageId="19" pageNumber="82">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,344,866,891]" pageId="19" pageNumber="82">Recognition.</emphasis>
In the key of 
<bibRefCitation author="Lundbeck, W." box="[502,691,866,891]" pageId="19" pageNumber="82" refId="ref7421" refString="Lundbeck, W. (1922) Diptera Danica. Part UI. Pipunculidae, Phoridae. Wesley, London, 455 pp." type="book" year="1922">Lundbeck (1922)</bibRefCitation>
to Group VII couplet 4 where the hypopygium clearly differs from that of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Wood)" authorityName="Wood" baseAuthorityName="Wood" baseAuthorityYear="1910" box="[229,457,902,927]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="82" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rufifrons">
<emphasis box="[229,361,903,927]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="82">M. rufifrons</emphasis>
(Wood)
</taxonomicName>
. It more closely resembles 
<taxonomicName authority="(Schmitz)" authorityName="Schmitz" baseAuthorityName="Schmitz" baseAuthorityYear="1919" box="[756,1017,902,927]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="82" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="praeacuta">
<emphasis box="[756,902,903,926]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="82">M. praeacuta</emphasis>
(Schmitz)
</taxonomicName>
but differs in having 6, not 3, axillary bristles, different costal ratios and vein 4 originating before the fork of vein 3 instead of beyond. In the key to the males of the British species (
<bibRefCitation author="Disney, R. H. L." box="[393,541,974,999]" pageId="19" pageNumber="82" pagination="1 - 155" refId="ref7235" refString="Disney, R. H. L. (1989) Scuttle Flies-Diptera Phoridae Genus Megaselia. Handbooks for the Identification of British Insects, 10 (8), 1 - 155." type="journal article" year="1989">Disney, 1989</bibRefCitation>
) it runs to couplet 283, but its hypopygium is immediately distinguished from that of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Wood)" authorityName="Wood" baseAuthorityName="Wood" baseAuthorityYear="1909" box="[182,406,1010,1035]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="82" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="frontalis">
<emphasis box="[182,312,1010,1035]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="82">M. frontalis</emphasis>
(Wood)
</taxonomicName>
and the latter’s longer costal index (at 0.48). However, it more closely resembles 
<taxonomicName authority="(Wood)" authorityName="Wood" baseAuthorityName="Wood" baseAuthorityYear="1910" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="82" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="maura">
<emphasis box="[1326,1436,1012,1035]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="82">M. maura</emphasis>
(Wood)
</taxonomicName>
. The latter has only 3–4 axillary bristles, as opposed to 6, and its vein 4 originates beyond the fork of vein 3, as opposed to before the fork. The hypopygia are similar but distinct (compare 
<figureCitation box="[975,1145,1082,1107]" captionStart="FIGURES 118–125" captionStartId="18.[151,264,1878,1901]" captionTargetBox="[187,1405,229,1822]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[150,1436,193,1858]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURES 118–125. Megaselia thomseni sp. n. male. 118. front of frons, postpedicels, palps and proboscis. 119. ventral view of proboscis. 120–121. hypopygium. 122. front tarsus. 123. mid femur and tibia.124. hind femur. 125. wing." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2617719/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="82">Figs 120 &amp; 121</figureCitation>
with 126 &amp; 127).
</paragraph>
